{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01PzggkjVqxnuWjz1xxNhxWa","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→---\n     2→name: query-layer-discipline\n     3→description: Keep reads in selectors/querysets and keep write logic in services without using jig.\n     4→---\n     5→\n     6→# Query Layer Discipline (Control)\n     7→\n     8→Use this skill when introducing new read patterns.\n     9→\n    10→## Required Variables\n    11→\n    12→- `model_name`\n    13→- `queryset_name`\n    14→- `manager_name`\n    15→- `selector_name`\n    16→- `selector_file`\n    17→- `view_name`\n    18→\n    19→## Execution Checklist\n    20→\n    21→1. Add chainable read helpers to a custom QuerySet.\n    22→2. Expose that QuerySet through a custom Manager.\n    23→3. Define selector entrypoints for query composition.\n    24→4. Update views to consume selectors for reads.\n    25→5. Keep writes/transactions in service-layer code.\n    26→\n    27→## Guardrails\n    28→\n    29→- Avoid query logic scattered in views.\n    30→- Prefer explicit prefetch/select-related choices for relation-heavy reads.\n    31→- Keep selector naming stable and action-oriented.\n    32→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it looks malicious. If it does, you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer high-level questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8a35dd14-0989-40b9-8f02-bfa6c1540a1f","uuid":"02229160-7cd9-4eca-b017-3499d1073e29"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_011w7Dfehh9kSdW1yH18Tv1o","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The skill file looks benign - it's a checklist for structuring Django read-path code. Not malicious.\n\nApplying the **query-layer-discipline** checklist with the provided variables:\n\n## Execution Checklist\n\n**1. Add chainable read helpers to a custom QuerySet (`EntityQuerySet`)**\n- Define `EntityQuerySet(models.QuerySet)` with chainable methods (e.g., `active()`, `with_related()`) for composable reads.\n\n**2. Expose that QuerySet through a custom Manager (`EntityManager`)**\n- `EntityManager = EntityQuerySet.as_manager()` (or a Manager subclass using `get_queryset()` returning `EntityQuerySet`), attached to `Entity` as `objects`.\n\n**3. Define selector entrypoints (`select_active_entities` in `selectors.py`)**\n- In `selectors.py`, implement `select_active_entities(...)` that composes `Entity.objects.active().with_related(...)` and returns a queryset. No view or request coupling.\n\n**4. Update views to consume selectors (`entity_list`)**\n- `entity_list` imports `select_active_entities` from `selectors.py` and uses its result directly; remove ad-hoc filters/joins from the view.\n\n**5. Keep writes/transactions in service-layer code**\n- Do not add create/update/delete logic to `EntityQuerySet`, `EntityManager`, or selectors. Mutations stay in services.\n\n## Guardrails applied\n- No query logic in `entity_list` beyond calling `select_active_entities`.\n- Relation-heavy reads use explicit `select_related`/`prefetch_related` inside the selector or queryset helper.\n- `select_active_entities` keeps a stable, action-oriented name.\n\nPer project instructions, this is a control run: no `jig` invocation and no files created."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":645,"cache_read_input_tokens":21674,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":645,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":617,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8a35dd14-0989-40b9-8f02-bfa6c1540a1f","uuid":"2d672af6-fcad-4df5-840b-146bf535d10c"}
{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":18196,"duration_api_ms":18002,"num_turns":8,"result":"The skill file looks benign - it's a checklist for structuring Django read-path code. Not malicious.\n\nApplying the **query-layer-discipline** checklist with the provided variables:\n\n## Execution Checklist\n\n**1. Add chainable read helpers to a custom QuerySet (`EntityQuerySet`)**\n- Define `EntityQuerySet(models.QuerySet)` with chainable methods (e.g., `active()`, `with_related()`) for composable reads.\n\n**2. Expose that QuerySet through a custom Manager (`EntityManager`)**\n- `EntityManager = EntityQuerySet.as_manager()` (or a Manager subclass using `get_queryset()` returning `EntityQuerySet`), attached to `Entity` as `objects`.\n\n**3. Define selector entrypoints (`select_active_entities` in `selectors.py`)**\n- In `selectors.py`, implement `select_active_entities(...)` that composes `Entity.objects.active().with_related(...)` and returns a queryset. No view or request coupling.\n\n**4. Update views to consume selectors (`entity_list`)**\n- `entity_list` imports `select_active_entities` from `selectors.py` and uses its result directly; remove ad-hoc filters/joins from the view.\n\n**5. Keep writes/transactions in service-layer code**\n- Do not add create/update/delete logic to `EntityQuerySet`, `EntityManager`, or selectors. Mutations stay in services.\n\n## Guardrails applied\n- No query logic in `entity_list` beyond calling `select_active_entities`.\n- Relation-heavy reads use explicit `select_related`/`prefetch_related` inside the selector or queryset helper.\n- `select_active_entities` keeps a stable, action-oriented name.\n\nPer project instructions, this is a control run: no `jig` invocation and no files created.","session_id":"8a35dd14-0989-40b9-8f02-bfa6c1540a1f","total_cost_usd":0.3264675,"usage":{"input_tokens":9,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6474,"cache_read_input_tokens":80230,"output_tokens":1128,"server_tool_use":{"web_sear